# PROJECT BRIEF — Desire Escorts Rebuild (Next.js + Strapi)

## Project Context

Desire Escorts currently runs on WordPress/Elementor with Dutch and English content (`/` and `/en/`) on [desire-escorts.nl](https://desire-escorts.nl/).
Escort profiles (products) have already moved to Strapi and will remain the source of truth for profile data, profile content, and availability status.

The website will be rebuilt in a modern Next.js/Node.js stack and migrated with SEO continuity as a non-negotiable.

## Primary Goal

Rebuild the website in Next.js while preserving current organic performance by mirroring existing pages, structure, internal links, and content as closely as possible at launch.

## Migration Principle

- Launch phase = parity-first migration:
  - Keep URLs stable.
  - Keep page intent and content blocks equivalent.
  - Keep internal linking structure equivalent.
- Allow minor editorial fixes during migration only when they do not alter:
  - URL structure
  - canonical intent
  - search intent alignment
- Post-launch phase = structured content optimization.

## Technical Direction

- Frontend: Next.js (Node.js runtime)
- CMS/Data source: Strapi
- Hosting and deployment: Vercel (preview + production environments)
- Delivery model: Git-based CI/CD with automated Vercel builds per branch/PR
- Legacy extraction sources:
  - WordPress export data
  - Firecrawl site extraction
  - XML sitemaps
- Content domains:
  - Core pages
  - Page structure/content blocks
  - Media assets
  - Blog content
  - Existing internal links
  - Current URL/sitemap topology

## Scope

### In Scope (Phase 1)

- Recreate existing NL and EN site architecture.
- Migrate all indexable pages required for parity launch.
- Integrate escort profile data and availability from Strapi.
- Preserve crawlability/indexability signals (metadata, canonicals, hreflang intent, internal links).
- Prepare redirect map for any unavoidable URL deltas (target: minimal to zero deltas).

### Out of Scope (Phase 1)

- Major content rewrites
- Aggressive IA changes
- Large-scale CRO redesign experiments
- Non-essential new page creation unrelated to current indexable footprint

## SEO Requirements (Non-Negotiable)

- Exact URL parity where technically possible.
- For Phase 1 launch, `meta title` and `meta description` must be exact text matches to the live legacy page for each URL+locale (`/` NL, `/en/` EN).
- Any title/description deviation requires explicit SEO approval and a documented exception before release.
- Preserve heading hierarchy at launch.
- Maintain internal linking pathways for key commercial and informational pages.
- Keep language paths stable (`/` NL, `/en/` EN) unless explicitly redefined.
- Preserve or improve Core Web Vitals and crawl efficiency.
- No accidental deindexing of currently valuable pages.
- Preserve technical SEO behavior through deployment (stable redirects, canonical output, and noindex controls per environment).

## Deployment and Environments

- Production deployment target is Vercel.
- Maintain separate preview and production environments for safe validation.
- Ensure environment variable strategy is defined for:
  - Strapi API access
  - analytics/search console integrations
  - any SEO/runtime feature flags
- Build pipeline must include pre-release SEO checks before production promotion.
- Rollback path must be documented and validated before launch.

## Content and Discovery Inputs

Migration discovery should combine:

- XML sitemap inventory (current truth for indexable URLs)
- WordPress export datasets (structured legacy source)
- Firecrawl outputs (rendered content and link graph)
- Media extraction and mapping
- Blog post archive extraction
- URL-level inventory + mapping manifest (legacy -> new)

## Expected Deliverables

- URL inventory (NL/EN) with migration status (`include`, `review`, `exclude`)
- Page-level content parity map
- Internal link retention map
- Media inventory + replacement mapping
- Blog migration dataset
- Redirect specification (if any deltas)
- Go-live SEO QA checklist and validation report

## Delivery Phases

1. Discovery and Inventory
   - Crawl and export all relevant sources.
   - Build canonical URL inventory and classify by type.

2. Mapping and Modeling
   - Map legacy content to new templates/components.
   - Confirm Strapi content model coverage for all required entities.

3. Build and Populate
   - Implement Next.js routes/templates.
   - Populate content and media with parity checks.

4. SEO QA and Pre-Launch
   - Validate metadata, canonicals, hreflang, indexability, links, and structured signals.
   - Validate parity versus legacy inventory.
   - Validate Vercel preview against launch checklist before production promotion.

5. Launch and Stabilization
   - Monitor indexing, rankings, traffic, crawl stats, and 404s.
   - Fix critical regressions immediately.

## Success Criteria

- All in-scope legacy URLs migrated or intentionally redirected.
- No critical SEO regressions in indexation/crawlability signals at launch.
- NL/EN parity delivered.
- `Meta title` and `meta description` exact-match parity is achieved for all in-scope URL+locale pairs, except approved exceptions.
- Escort profile + availability powered by Strapi in production.
- Content parity achieved with only approved minor editorial changes.

## Risks to Manage

- Hidden legacy pages not present in standard sitemap exports
- Media mismatches or broken references
- Internal link graph degradation
- Metadata drift between old and new templates
- Hreflang/canonical implementation inconsistencies
- Unexpected Strapi schema/content gaps during integration

## Governance

- Any change that may affect SEO parity requires explicit approval.
- Parity-first decisions override improvement-first decisions during Phase 1.
- Optimization backlog is recorded and prioritized for post-launch iterations.
